column36:
Here is a look at the priorities from the Seattle Electric Vehicle Association to consider:   EV POLICY UPDATE 1-15-24

Hello electric vehicle advocates! Happy MLK Day! The first week of this year's short legislative session in Olympia included action on the direct vehicle sales ban (without any hearing) in the Senate and scheduling a hearing on the ban companion bill this week in the House. Two other bills of interest to SEVA have hearings coming up this week. Here is a summary of what's happened already and what's coming up and how you can participate:

THIS WEEK

House Bill 1368, reintroduced after it made progress in the House last session. Requiring and funding purchases of zero-emission school buses after September 2035. Sponsor Rep. Senn. Following a public hearing on Jan. 11, the bill is scheduled for executive session and a possible vote at 4 p.m. Jan. 18 in the House Appropriations Committee. Companion bill SB5431 has been reintroduced and referred to the Senate Committee on Early Learning & K-12 Education. The bill requires purchasing zero-emission school buses after Sept. 1, 2035. It would create a grant program using any specifically appropriated funding to support school districts, charter schools, and state-tribal education compact schools purchasing them, and to support purchasing and installing charging stations and associated infrastructure and equipment. To be eligible for grants, buses powered by fossil fuels would have to be at the end of their depreciation schedule and eligible for replacement under the current state law about reimbursing districts for the cost of student transportation vehicles. Read text here. Submit your testimony here.

Senate Bill 5812 - Requiring a study of best practices for responding to electric vehicle fires. Sponsors Sen. Jeff Wilson and Sen. Nguyen. Public hearing at 4 p.m. Thursday, Jan. 18 in the Senate Transportation Committee. The bill requires the Washington State Patrol to do a study of electric vehicle fires in consultation with the Department of Ecology and local fire protection districts, covering environmental and health effects, and best practices for response, clean-up and disposal. Read text here. Submit testimony here.

SB5945 - Prohibiting direct retail sales or leases of vehicles and some subscription services; limiting manufacturers’ ability to get dealers to install fast chargers. Sponsor Sen. Conway. Companion bill HB2028. Passed out of the Senate Business, Financial Services, Gaming & Trade Committee on Jan. 9 without a hearing and without recommendation. Referred to the Senate Labor and Commerce Committee. Prohibits direct sales or leases of vehicles to retail customers. Prohibits offering consumers a subscription service for any vehicle feature that uses components and hardware that are already on the vehicle when it’s purchased or leased. Prevents manufacturers and distributors from creating programs or policies encouraging or requiring dealers to install direct current fast charging stations. Prohibits manufacturers from implementing an incentive program that did not provide an equal opportunity for all dealers to qualify because of their location or sales volume. Read text here. Submit testimony here. Companion bill HB2028 is sponsored by Rep. Santos. Public hearing is scheduled at 1:30 p.m. Wednesday, Jan. 17, in the House Consumer Protection & Business Committee. Read text here. Submit testimony here.

In regard to SB 5945 and HB2028, Rivian is again fighting for direct EV sales in Washington. If you would like to help, you can learn more at Rivian Direct Sales (directevsales.com). 

NEW

HB1868 - Restricting new gas outdoor lawn equipment and providing grants and tax breaks for electric alternatives. Sponsor Rep. Walen. Introduced Jan. 8 and referred to the House Environment and Energy Committee. The bill requires DOE to adopt rules to prohibit engine exhaust and evaporative emissions from outdoor power equipment with less than 25 horsepower produced on or after Jan. 1, 2026. Government emergency response equipment is exempt. Creates a 6-year exemption from sales tax for zero-emission equipment. Read text here. Submit testimony here.

HB2051 - Reducing emissions from small off-road engines. Sponsor Rep. Walen. Referred to the House Environment and Energy Committee. The bill adopts California’s small off-road engine and equipment emissions standards for engines and equipment produced after January 1st, 2027. Creates a five-year program providing grants for local governments to replace working outdoor power equipment. Creates a sales tax exemption for zero-emission outdoor equipment producing less than 25 horsepower, and for push lawn mowers. Read text here. Submit testimony here.

HB2189 - Exempting regular hybrids, which can’t be charged with an external electrical power source, from the additional $75 registration fee they and plugin vehicles currently pay. Sponsor Rep Kloba. Referred to the House Transportation Committee. Exempts hybrid vehicles that can't be recharged from an external power source from paying the annual $75 transportation electrification fee, which goes toward installation of charging stations. Read text here. Submit testimony here.

House Joint Memorial 4003 - Advocating a Fossil Fuel Nonproliferation Treaty. Sponsor Rep. Street. Referred to the House Environment and Energy Committee. The bill urges the US government to participate in developing a Fossil Fuel Nonproliferation Treaty as an international mechanism to manage a global transition away from coal, oil, and gas, and affirms the need for a plan to phase out fossil fuel production. Read text here. Submit testimony here.

SB5872 - Requires a human safety operator in any autonomous vehicle operated on the highway. Sponsor Sen. Lovick. Referred to Senate Transportation Committee Jan. 8. Requires a human safety operator to be physically present in any autonomous vehicle operated on the highway to monitor its performance and intervene if necessary, The safety operator would have to meet any state or federal requirements for operating a motor vehicle. Read text here. Submit testimony here.

SB5909 - Reimbursing tow truck operators for the towing, transport, and storage of electric vehicles; providing grants to protect facilities from risks associated with storing them. Sponsor Sen. Jeff Wilson. Referred to the Senate Transportation Committee. The bill authorizes the Department of Licensing to develop a program reimbursing tow truck operators for towing, transporting, and storing electric vehicles. Reimbursements would be limited to a maximum of $10,000 per vehicle; funding for them would come from the additional $75 transportation electrification fee. Requires the Department of Commerce to create a program awarding grants to registered operators for retrofitting storage facilities to provide for additional protections to accommodate electric vehicles. Read text here. Submit testimony here.

SB5951 - Repealing the State’s authorization to allow charging by the public at locations where it’s providing the power. Sponsor Sen. Schoesler. Referred to the Senate State Government and Elections Committee. The bill would repeal the current provision authorizing the State to allow charging by the general public and by people who are there conducting business with the State at locations where it’s providing the power. Read text here. Submit testimony here.

HOW TO TESTIFY:

If you haven't registered your comments yet, it takes just a minute to sign in with your support or opposition. The online Committee Sign In portal allows you to register your support or opposition to a bill, submit a comment for a public hearing, or sign up to testify online on a Senate or House bill.

You also can call and e-mail your state senators and representatives directly - find your district, names and e-mail addresses at www.leg.wa.gov.
I plan to send out weekly updates during the legislative session, highlighting opportunities to share your thoughts and concerns. Please share with anyone you know who is interested!

Grace
vicepresident@seattleeva.org
